      "content": "Apologies for the confusion. Let's dive straight into the technical mechanics of the pitot-static system. The pitot tube measures the dynamic pressure of the air flowing into it, which is the pressure due to the aircraft's motion. This dynamic pressure is the difference between the total pressure (measured by the pitot tube) and the static pressure (measured by the static ports) surrounding the aircraft.\n\nThe total pressure (P_total) is the sum of the static pressure (P_static) and the dynamic pressure (P_dynamic). Mathematically, it can be expressed as:\n\nP_total = P_static + P_dynamic\n\nThe dynamic pressure can be calculated using Bernoulli's equation, which in its simplest form for incompressible flow is:\n\nP_dynamic = 0.5 * ρ * V^2\n\nwhere ρ is the air density and V is the velocity of the aircraft relative to the air.\n\nThe static pressure (P_static) is measured by the static ports, which are small holes on the aircraft's surface that are not directly exposed to the airflow. This pressure is what the aircraft experiences while at rest or moving at a constant speed.\n\nThe pitot tube, which is exposed to the airflow, measures the total",
